LinkedHashSet in Java

LinkedHashSet is a class in Java that implements the Set interface.

It stores unique elements like HashSet, but also preserves insertion order.

How LinkedHashSet works

LinkedHashSet is based on:

a HashSet (for fast operations)
a linked list (to maintain order)

👉 This gives:

uniqueness
predictable order
good performance
Key Features
no duplicates
maintains insertion order
allows one null value
not thread-safe
slightly slower than HashSet
Creating a LinkedHashSet
import java.util.LinkedHashSet;
import java.util.Set;

Set<String> set = new LinkedHashSet<>();
Example
set.add("Banana");
set.add("Apple");
set.add("Orange");

System.out.println(set);

👉 Output:

[Banana, Apple, Orange]

👉 Order is preserved as inserted

Common Methods
set.add("Apple");
set.remove("Apple");
set.contains("Apple");
set.size();
Performance
Operation	Complexity
add()	O(1)
remove()	O(1)
contains()	O(1)

👉 slightly slower than HashSet due to maintaining order

LinkedHashSet vs HashSet vs TreeSet
Feature	HashSet	LinkedHashSet	TreeSet
Duplicates	❌	❌	❌
Order	❌	✅ (insertion)	✅ (sorted)
Speed	Fastest	Slightly slower	Slowest
When to use LinkedHashSet

Use it when:

you need unique elements
you want to preserve insertion order
performance still matters
When NOT to use
need sorted data → use TreeSet
order does not matter → use HashSet
Summary
LinkedHashSet = HashSet + order
stores unique elements
maintains insertion order
fast (O(1))
good balance between speed and order
